'''Block, Inc.''' (formerly '''Square, Inc.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Browning |first1=Kellen |date=December 1, 2021 |title=Square, Jack Dorsey's payments company, changes its name to Block. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/12/01/technology/square-block-name-change-dorsey.html?action=click&module=Well&pgtype=Homepage&section=Technology |access-date=December 2, 2021 |work=The New York Times}}</ref>''') is an American technology company that provides [[financial services]] to consumers and merchants.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Poritz |first=Isaiah |date=2023-01-23 |title=Block Inc. Can Keep Using Name in H&R Block Trademark Spat |url=https://news.bloomberglaw.com/ip-law/block-inc-can-keep-using-name-in-trademark-spat-with-h-r-block |access-date=2024-10-02 |website=Bloomberg Law}}</ref><ref name=":24" /><ref name=":27" /> Founded in 2009 by [[Jack Dorsey]], it is the U.S. market leader in [[Point of sale|point-of-sale]] systems.<ref name=":2" /><ref name=":21">{{Cite web |last=Rivera |first=David |date=2024-04-02 |title=21 Point-of-Sale Statistics to Know in 2024 |url=https://fitsmallbusiness.com/point-of-sale-statistics/ |access-date=2024-09-16 |website=Fit Small Business |language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=":22">{{Cite web |last=Elliott |first=Jessica |date=2024-05-27 |title=What Is a Point-of-Sale (POS) System? |url=https://www.uschamber.com/co/run/technology/what-is-a-pos-system |access-date=2024-09-16 |website=www.uschamber.com |language=en-US}}</ref> As of 2023, Block serves 56 million users and 4 million sellers,<ref name=":23">{{Cite web |last=Coleman |first=Sara |date=2024-04-10 |title=Square Credit Card Processing Review |url=https://www.usnews.com/360-reviews/business/credit-card-processing/square |website=usnews.com}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite web |last=Sigalos |first=MacKenzie |date=February 22, 2024 |title=Block shares surge as much as 14% after company announces surprise profit |url=https://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/business/money-report/block-shares-surge-12-after-announcing-surprise-profit/3346302/ |access-date=February 23, 2024 |website=NBC Los Angeles |language=en-US}}</ref> processing $228 billion in payments annually.<ref name="10K2023" />

Block's inaugural product [[Square (payment system)|''Square'']], launched in 2009, is a point-of-sale system.<ref name=":2" /> It allows sellers to accept card payments and manage operations, including bookings,<ref name=":16">{{Cite web |last1=Clague |first1=Casey |last2=Ballard |first2=Danielle |date=2024-07-30 |title=Square pricing in 2024 |url=https://edition.cnn.com/cnn-underscored/money/square-pricing |access-date=2024-10-22 |website=CNN}}</ref> [[E-commerce|e-Commerce]],<ref name=":25">{{Cite web |last1=McAlpine |first1=Cat |last2=Campbell |first2=Sierra |date=2024-10-04 |title=Square vs. Squarespace: Differences, Pros and Cons in 2024 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/money/blueprint/business/website-builders/square-vs-squarespace/ |access-date=2024-10-22 |website=USA TODAY}}</ref> inventory,<ref name=":28">{{Cite web |last1=Uher |first1=Amanda |last2=Ballard |first2=Danielle |last3=Cother |first3=Jason |date=2024-10-03 |title=Square vs. Shopify: Which is best in 2024? |url=https://edition.cnn.com/cnn-underscored/money/square-vs-shopify |access-date=2024-10-22 |website=CNN}}</ref> payroll, shift scheduling a,<ref name=":6" /> banking, and obtaining [[Business loan|business loans]].<ref name=":7" /> Additionally, Block's portfolio includes [[Cash App|''Cash App'']], a consumer-focused [[digital wallet]] introduced in 2013.<ref name=":24">{{Cite magazine |last=Alfaro |first=Isabel Peña |date=2023-03-02 |title=What is Cash App & How Does It Work? |url=https://time.com/personal-finance/article/what-is-cash-app/ |access-date=2024-09-26 |magazine=Time |language=en-US |issn=0040-781X}}</ref><ref name=":20" /> This service allows users to send, receive or save money,<ref name=":8" /><ref name=":9" /> access a debit card, invest in stocks and [[bitcoin]],<ref name=":10" /><ref name=":11" /> apply for [[personal loans]],<ref name=":13" /> and file taxes.<ref name=":12" /> Block also owns ''[[Afterpay]]'', a [[buy now, pay later]] service;<ref name=":14" /> ''[[Bitkey]]'', a self-custody [[Bitcoin#Wallets|bitcoin wallet]];<ref name=":18">{{Cite web |last=Sureban |first=BL Bengaluru Bureau & Haripriya |date=December 7, 2023 |title=Block Inc launches self-custody bitcoin wallet Bitkey in India |url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/money-and-banking/block-inc-launches-self-custody-bitcoin-wallet-bitkey-in-india/article67615124.ece |access-date=February 5, 2024 |website=BusinessLine |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":19">{{Cite web |title=Jack Dorsey's Block opens up preorders for Bitcoin hardware wallet Bitkey in more than 95 countries |url=https://fortune.com/crypto/2023/12/07/jack-dorseys-block-bitkey-preorders-live-95-countries-bitcoin-hardware-wallet/ |access-date=February 5, 2024 |website=Fortune Crypto |language=en}}</ref> a [[bitcoin mining]] hardware business;<ref name=":29">{{Cite web |last=Nishant |first=Niket |date=2024-07-11 |title=Block investors need more to gauge crypto unit's earnings potential, analysts say |url=https://www.reuters.com/technology/block-investors-need-more-gauge-crypto-units-earnings-potential-analysts-say-2024-07-11/ |access-date=2024-11-10 |website=[[Reuters]]}}</ref><ref name=":30">{{Cite web |last=Sigalos |first=MacKenzie |date=2024-04-23 |title=Jack Dorsey's payments company, Block, is building its own bitcoin mining system |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2024/04/23/block-formerly-square-building-its-own-bitcoin-mining-system.html |access-date=2024-11-10 |website=[[CNBC]] |language=en}}</ref> and [[Tidal (service)|''Tidal'']], a [[music streaming]] service.<ref name=":17">{{Cite web |last=Rosman |first=Katherine |date=March 4, 2021 |title=Square Acquires Tidal in $297 Million Deal |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/03/04/business/media/tidal-square-jay-z-dorsey.html |access-date=October 30, 2023 |website=The New York Times |language=en-US}}</ref>

==History==

=== 2009: Conception ===
The original inspiration for Block's first product "Square" occurred to [[Jack Dorsey]] in 2009 when his friend [[Jim McKelvey]] was unable to complete a $2,000 sale of his glass faucets and fittings because he could not accept credit cards.<ref>{{Cite web |date=May 11, 2010 |title=Square Brings Credit Card Swiping to the Mobile Masses, Starting Today |url=http://www.fastcompany.com/1643271/square-brings-credit-card-swiping-mobile-masses-starting-today |access-date=September 19, 2011 |website=Fast Company}}</ref> Co-founders Dorsey—who also co-founded [[Twitter, Inc.|Twitter]]—and McKelvey began developing the company out of a small office in St. Louis.<ref>{{Cite web |date=September 15, 2015 |title=Why Square's New Office Is A Really Big Deal for St. Louis |url=https://www.stlmag.com/news/why-square-new-office-is-a-really-big-deal-for-st-louis/ |work=St. Louis Magazine}}</ref> The name "Square" derives from the company's square-shaped card reader product.<ref>{{Cite web |date=May 26, 2011 |title=Square's name and design were changed by a lunch at Apple |url=https://thenextweb.com/apple/2011/05/26/squares-name-and-design-were-changed-by-a-lunch-at-apple/ |access-date=September 19, 2011 |publisher=thenextweb.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=May 26, 2011 |title=Square Was Almost Named Squirrel Until Dorsey Talked To Apple |url=http://pulse2.com/2011/05/26/square-was-almost-named-squirrel-until-dorsey-talked-to-apple/ |access-date=September 19, 2011 |publisher=pulse2.com}}</ref>

=== 2010–2014: Early years ===
According to ''[[Forbes]]'', Block, named Square, Inc. then, tested its payment method on 50,000 merchants in the summer of 2010, and was reporting a [[chargeback]] rate of less than 0.05 percent.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Upbin |first=Bruce |date=November 5, 2010 |title=Names You Need To Know in 2011: Square |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/bruceupbin/2010/11/05/names-you-need-to-know-in-2011-square/ |access-date=March 4, 2024 |website=Forbes |language=en}}</ref> In February 2011, Square was reportedly valued at approximately US$240 million, signing up 100,000 new merchants every month.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Rubin |first=Courtney |date=February 23, 2011 |title=Mobile Payment Firm Square Drops Transaction Fee |url=https://www.inc.com/news/articles/201102/square-drops-credit-card-transaction-fee.html |website=inc.com}}</ref> In April 2011, Square announced that it has secured an investment from [[Visa Inc.|Visa]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Barth |first=Chris |date=April 27, 2011 |title=Visa And Square: Why Goliath Is Investing In David |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/chrisbarth/2011/04/27/visa-and-square-why-goliath-is-investing-in-david/ |access-date=March 4, 2024 |website=Forbes |language=en}}</ref> In October 2011, the company stated that it was processing about US$2 billion per year in payments through its "Square" card readers, charging 2.75 percent per swipe.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Reisinger |first=Don |date=March 5, 2012 |title=Square launches iPad app; adios, cash register |url=https://www.cnet.com/home/smart-home/square-launches-ipad-app-adios-cash-register/ |access-date=March 4, 2024 |website=CNET |language=en}}</ref>

In 2012, [[Starbucks]] and Square announced a partnership that would allow Starbucks to use the Square payment technology to accept payments for coffee. In the same year, Starbucks also reportedly invested in Square at a valuation of US$25 million.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Gasparro |first1=Annie |last2=Efrati |first2=Amir |date=August 8, 2012 |title=Starbucks to Use Square Inc.'s Mobile-Payments Technology |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10000872396390444423704577575803898185594 |access-date=March 4, 2024 |work=WSJ |language=en-US}}</ref> Square was handling an annual payment volume of around US$6 billion around that time.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Segall |first=Laurie |date=October 9, 2012 |title=Square CEO Jack Dorsey scales back at Twitter |url=https://money.cnn.com/2012/10/09/technology/social/jack-dorsey-square/index.html |access-date=March 4, 2024 |website=CNNMoney}}</ref>

In 2013, Square launched Cash App, a peer to peer payment service.<ref name=":9" /> In October 2014, the company launched the integration of a payroll feature into its Square payment processing system, following the integrations of a merchant cash advance offering, a customer feedback product and an invoicing service into the system.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Rey |first=Jason Del |date=October 20, 2014 |title=Square Testing New Payroll Product as Ambition Grows |url=https://www.vox.com/2014/10/20/11632052/square-testing-new-payroll-product-as-ambition-grows |access-date=March 4, 2024 |website=Vox |language=en}}</ref>

=== 2015–2020: Initial public offering, growth ===
In 2015, Square stated that it processed about US$23.8 billion worth of payment volume in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Mac |first=Ryan |date=October 30, 2015 |title=Amazon Kills Credit Card Reader And Square Competitor, 'Register' |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ryanmac/2015/10/30/amazon-kills-credit-card-reader-and-square-competitor-register/ |access-date=March 4, 2024 |website=Forbes |language=en}}</ref> In the same year, the company sold shares in its initial public offering for US$9 per share, giving itself a market capitalization of $2.9 billion.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Mac |first=Ryan |date=November 18, 2015 |title=Square Prices IPO Below Range At $9 A Share, Now Valued at $2.9 Billion |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ryanmac/2015/11/18/square-prices-ipo-below-range-at-9-a-share-now-valued-at-2-9-billion/ |access-date=March 4, 2024 |website=Forbes |language=en}}</ref>

In 2018, [[Vox Media|Vox]] reported Square as stating that over 7 million people used the Cash App in December 2017. Vox also stated that Cash App was the "No. 1 free finance app" in [[Apple Inc.|Apple's]] U.S. [[iPhone App Store]] and was "ahead" of [[PayPal]] and [[Venmo]].<ref name=":20">{{Cite web |last=Rey |first=Jason Del |date=February 27, 2018 |title=Square's Venmo competitor — the Cash app — had more than seven million customers in December |url=https://www.vox.com/2018/2/27/17059182/square-cash-app-monthly-active-users-customers-seven-million-december-venmo |access-date=March 4, 2024 |website=Vox |language=en}}</ref>

In October 2020, Square put approximately 1% of their total assets ($50 million) in [[Bitcoin]] (4,709 bitcoins), citing Bitcoin's "potential to be a more ubiquitous currency in the future" as their main reasoning.<ref>{{Cite web |author=Oliver Effron |title=Square just bought $50 million in bitcoin |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/10/08/business/square-bitcoin-crypto-investment/index.html |access-date=October 22, 2020 |website=CNN|date=October 8, 2020 }}</ref> The company purchased approximately 3,318 bitcoins in February 2021 for a cost of around $170 million, bringing Square's total holdings to around 8,027 bitcoins (equivalent to around US$500 million in 2021, around US$481 million as of July 2024).<ref>{{Cite web|last=Bursztynsky|first=Jessica|date=February 23, 2021|title=Square buys $170 million worth of bitcoin|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2021/02/23/square-buys-170-million-worth-of-bitcoin.html|access-date=March 2, 2021|website=CNBC|language=en}}</ref>

=== 2021–present: Name change, acquisitions ===
On March 2, 2021, Square reached an agreement to acquire majority ownership in [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]. Square paid $297 million in cash and stock for Tidal, with [[Jay-Z]] joining the company's board of directors. Jay-Z, as well as other artists who currently own stock in Tidal, will remain stakeholders.<ref>{{cite web |title=Square, Inc. to buy majority of Tidal and put Jay-Z on board |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/wireStory/square-buy-majority-tidal-put-jay-board-76248384 |work=ABC News |agency=Associated Press |access-date=March 4, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Murphy Kelly |first1=Samantha |title=Square to acquire majority stake in music service Tidal for $297 million |date=March 4, 2021 |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/03/04/tech/square-tidal/index.html |publisher=CNN |access-date=March 4, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Singleton |first1=Micah |title=Square Is Acquiring a Majority Stake in Tidal for $297M |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/streaming/9534646/square-tidal-acquisition-majority-stake-jay-z |magazine=Billboard |access-date=March 5, 2021}}</ref>

On December 1, 2021, Square announced that it would change its company name to Block, Inc. on December 10.<ref name=wsj_block>{{Cite news|last=Vigna|first=Paul|date=December 1, 2021|title=Square Changes Name to Block, Days After CEO Jack Dorsey Leaves Twitter|language=en-US|work=Wall Street Journal|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/square-changes-name-to-block-days-after-ceo-jack-dorsey-leaves-twitter-11638394200|access-date=December 1, 2021|issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref>{{Cite press release|date=December 1, 2021|title=Square, Inc. Changes Name to Block|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20211201006139/en/Square-Inc.-Changes-Name-to-Block|access-date=December 1, 2021|publisher=Block, Inc.|via=[[Business Wire]]|language=en}}</ref> The change was announced shortly after Dorsey resigned as CEO of Twitter.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wagner |first1=Kurt |title=Square Changes Name to Block in Nod to New Businesses |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2021-12-01/dorsey-s-square-changes-name-to-block-in-nod-to-new-businesses?sref=CIpmV6x8 |access-date=December 2, 2021 |work=Bloomberg |date=December 1, 2021}}</ref> On December 10, 2021, the name change took effect, and Square, Inc. became Block, Inc.<ref name="cnbc.com">{{cite web |title=Jack Dorsey's Square changes corporate name to Block |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2021/12/01/square-changes-corporate-name-to-block-.html |access-date=December 10, 2021 |website=CNBC|date=December 2021 }}</ref> On December 16, less than a week into the rebrand, [[H&R Block]], sued the company for [[trademark infringement]], claiming that the name seeks to confuse customers by misappropriating the Block brand name, which H&R owns.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2021-12-16/h-r-block-claims-jack-dorsey-s-block-inc-violates-trademark| title=H&R Block Is Suing Jack Dorsey's Block Over Name Change |website=Bloomberg | date=December 16, 2021 |access-date=December 16, 2021}}</ref> The lawsuit was resolved in April 2023 when the two companies jointly agreed to dismiss the suit.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Brittain |first=Blake |date=April 24, 2023 |title=H&R Block settles trademark lawsuit against Block over name change |language=en |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/legal/hr-block-agrees-drop-trademark-lawsuit-against-block-over-name-change-2023-04-24/ |access-date=September 30, 2023}}</ref>

On January 31, 2022, Block completed its acquisition of [[Afterpay]], an Australian buy now, pay later (BNPL) lender.<ref name="completed acquistion"/>

On September 7 and 8, 2023, Block's Square and Cash App experienced outages, affecting thousands of users. Card payment processing, peer-to-peer payments and other transactions were among the impacted operations. On September 8, 2023, Block informed that the service disruptions had been resolved and all systems were operational by the afternoon of that day. It also said the outage was caused by an issue with the company's [[Domain Name System]] (DNS), and did not stem from a [[cyberattack]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Schulz |first=Bailey |date=2023-09-08 |title=What's going on with Cash App and Square? Square sheds light on last week's outage |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2023/09/08/square-cash-app-outage-issues/70794938007/ |access-date=2024-10-18 |website=USA TODAY |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Napolitano |first=Elizabeth |date=2023-09-08 |title=Cash App, Square users report payment issues amid service outage - CBS News |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/cash-app-down-square-service-outage/ |access-date=2024-10-18 |website=CBS News |language=en-US}}</ref> In the following week, Block apologized to its customers and acknowledged “this situation was made more difficult by our communication”. To reduce the risk of a similar outage in future, the company said it had deployed a new set of [[Firewall (computing)|firewall]] and DNS server changes, expanded offline payment capabilities so merchants can still accept payments in offline mode, and put in place additional measures.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Mullen |first=Caitlin |date=2023-09-14 |title=Square apologizes for last week's outage |url=https://www.paymentsdive.com/news/square-outage-pos-payments-processing-block-smb-merchants/693674/ |access-date=2024-10-18 |website=Payments Dive |language=en-US}}</ref> Later in the month, Block said in a regulatory filing that the CEO of its Square business, Alyssa Henry, was set to leave the company in October 2023, and that Jack Dorsey, serving then as the "Block Head" and Chairperson, would take on an additional role of "Square Head".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Thorbecke |first=Catherine |date=2023-09-18 |title=Square CEO Alyssa Henry is stepping down, and Jack Dorsey will take over for now {{!}} CNN Business |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2023/09/18/tech/square-ceo-steps-down/index.html/ |access-date=2024-10-18 |website=CNN |language=en}}</ref>

In February 2024, Block reported an annual "Gross Payment Volume" of US$228 billion and an annual income of $9.8 million for the year 2023.<ref name="10K2023" /> In April 2024, [[CNBC]] reported that Block announced it had finished the development of its own standalone three-nanometer bitcoin mining chip and was in the process of working through the design with a [[semiconductor foundry]]. The company was also reported to be developing a "full bitcoin mining system", stating that its goal was to both decentralize the supply of bitcoin mining hardware and the distribution of [[hashrate]] — a proxy for industry competition and mining difficulty. In this regard, according to CNBC, Block was solving a "major barrier to entry" posed by the relative difficulty in sourcing mining rigs, their high prices and unpredictable delivery.<ref name=":30" /> In May 2024, the company's Square platform was found to be the market leader in point-of-sale systems in the U.S.<ref name=":22" /><ref name=":21" /> In July 2024, Block signed a "large-scale crypto mining hardware pact", agreeing to supply its chips to bitcoin miner "Core Scientific". The company did not disclose financial details of the pact.<ref name=":29" /><ref name=":31">{{Cite web |last=Daley |first=Will |date=2024-07-11 |title=Block in Pact to Supply Bitcoin Mining Chip to Core Scientific |url=https://news.bloomberglaw.com/crypto/block-in-pact-to-supply-bitcoin-mining-chip-to-core-scientific |access-date=2024-11-10 |website=[[Bloomberg Law]]}}</ref> In October 2024, Bitkey appeared in [[Time (magazine)|''TIME's'']] list of the "best inventions of 2024".<ref name=":39">{{Cite web |title=200 Best Inventions of 2024 |url=https://time.com/collection/best-inventions-2024/ |access-date=2024-11-22 |website=TIME |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":40">{{Cite web |last=Klein |first=Jessica |date=2024-10-30 |title=Block Bitkey: the 200 Best Inventions of 2024 |url=https://time.com/7094838/block-bitkey/ |access-date=2024-11-22 |website=TIME |language=en}}</ref> In November 2024, ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' reported that Block was laying off many employees from its Tidal, TBD and Square services.<ref name=":37">{{Cite web |last=Hays |first=Kali |title=Employees at Jack Dorsey's Block were ordered not to discuss board member Jay-Z amid more layoffs |url=https://fortune.com/2024/11/07/block-jack-dorsey-jay-z-layoffs/ |access-date=2024-11-08 |website=Fortune |language=en}}</ref> That same month, Block announced it was "winding down" TBD, "scaling back" investments in Tidal and focussing its resources on its bitcoin mining initiative as well as Bitkey, while adding that it was "refining" its investments based on progress.<ref name=":32">{{Cite news |last1=Mason |first1=Emily |last2=Smith |first2=Paige |date=2024-11-07 |title=Block Tumbles After Quarterly Revenue Is Less Than Forecast |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-11-07/block-tumbles-after-quarterly-revenue-is-less-than-forecast |access-date=2024-11-08 |work=Bloomberg |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":33">{{Cite web |last1=Levy |first1=Ari |last2=Sigalos |first2=MacKenzie |date=2024-11-08 |title=Jack Dorsey dramatically scales back crypto ambitions for Block |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2024/11/08/jack-dorsey-dramatically-shutters-blocks-tbd-crypto-unit.html |access-date=2024-11-10 |website=[[CNBC]] |language=en}}</ref>

==Subsidiaries, products, services==

===Square===
{{Main|Square (payment system)}}
Square is a payments platform that allows businesses to accept card payments and use smartphones or tablets or computers as payment registers for a [[Point-of-sale|point-of-sale system]] (POS).<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Buskirk |first=Eliot Van |title=Twitter Creator Launches 'Square' -- Like Smartphone Paypal for Credit Cards |url=https://www.wired.com/2009/12/twitter-co-founder-launches-square-like-smartphone-paypal-for-credit-cards/ |access-date=2024-09-26 |magazine=Wired |language=en-US |issn=1059-1028}}</ref><ref name=":2">{{Cite web |last=Morrison |first=Sara |date=October 7, 2022 |title=Everyone wants a tip now. Do you have to give them one? |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2022/10/7/23389885/square-toast-tipping-retail-tipflation-guilt |access-date=October 30, 2023 |website=Vox |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=September 11, 2023 |title=Square POS Reviews & Ratings 2023 |url=https://www.trustradius.com/products/square-pos/reviews |access-date=November 2, 2023 |website=www.trustradius.com |language=en-US}}</ref> The platform was founded in 2009 by Dorsey and McKelvey. Square also offers additional features to manage various operations including staff payroll and shift schedules,<ref name=":6">{{Cite web |last=O'Reilly |first=Dennis |date=May 25, 2023 |title=Square Payroll Software Review and Prices |url=https://www.usnews.com/360-reviews/business/payroll-software/block |access-date=October 30, 2023 |website=U.S. News & World Report}}</ref> customer bookings,<ref name=":16" /><ref name=":3">{{Cite web |last=Sherman |first=Matt |date=October 24, 2023 |title=Square Appointments Review |url=https://www.merchantmaverick.com/reviews/square-appointments-review/ |access-date=October 30, 2023 |website=Merchant Maverick |language=en}}</ref> inventory,<ref name=":28" /> e-Commerce,<ref name=":25" /><ref name=":4">{{Cite web |last=Smith |first=Amy Nichol |date=February 22, 2022 |title=Square Online Store Review 2023: Features, Pros & Cons – Forbes Advisor |url=https://www.forbes.com/advisor/business/software/square-online-review/ |access-date=November 3, 2023 |website=www.forbes.com}}</ref><ref name=":5">{{Cite web |last=Stevens |first=Courtenay |date=December 14, 2022 |title=Everything You Need to Know about Square Inventory Management |url=https://www.business.org/finance/inventory-management/square-inventory-review/ |access-date=November 3, 2023 |website=Business.org |language=en-US}}</ref> banking and business loans.<ref name=":7">{{Cite news |last=Irrera |first=Anna |date=July 20, 2021 |title=Square launches small business banking |language=en |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/business/finance/square-launches-small-business-banking-2021-07-20/ |access-date=October 30, 2023}}</ref>

In 2022, a [[Protocol (website)|Protocol]] survey showed that 35% of U.S. small business owners used Square, a higher percentage than its competitors, while also highlighting the POS market's continued fragmentation.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Geron |first=Tomio |date=January 5, 2022 |title=Square, Clover and Lightspeed are popular, but no POS provider dominates - Protocol |url=https://www.protocol.com/fintech/small-business-fintech-survey-2022/small-business-survey-pos |access-date=November 16, 2023 |website=www.protocol.com |language=en}}</ref> In April 2023, Square was reported to have 4 million merchants as its customers.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |last=Mullen |first=Caitlin |date=April 18, 2023 |title=Square rolls out new features for merchants |url=https://www.retaildive.com/news/square-rolls-out-new-features-block-payments-merchant-services-smbs/647580/ |access-date=November 15, 2023 |website=Retail Dive |language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=":23" /> Its client base includes [[small and medium-sized businesses]] as well as larger ones.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Shweta |first=Shweta |date=2024-04-23 |title=Square Review 2024: Features, Pros & Cons – Forbes Advisor |url=https://www.forbes.com/advisor/business/software/square-review/ |access-date=2024-09-16 |website=www.forbes.com}}</ref><ref name=":27">{{Cite news |last=Wang |first=Selina |date=2017-02-22 |title=Square Tops Sales Estimates on Growth of Bigger Merchants |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-02-22/square-tops-sales-estimates-on-growth-of-bigger-sized-merchants |access-date=2024-10-21 |work=Bloomberg |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":26">{{Cite web |last=Mullen |first=Caitlin |date=2023-02-22 |title=Square chases bigger merchants |url=https://www.paymentsdive.com/news/square-chases-bigger-merchants-payments-pos-restaurants-retail/643225/ |access-date=2024-10-21 |website=Payments Dive |language=en-US}}</ref> As of 2024, the platform is available in the U.S., Australia, Canada, France, Japan, Republic of Ireland, Spain and the U.K.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Davies |first1=Rhiân |last2=McHugh |first2=Kevin |last3=Coates |first3=Kristen |date=2024-04-29 |title=Stripe vs. Square: Which is best in 2024? |url=https://edition.cnn.com/cnn-underscored/money/stripe-vs-square |access-date=2024-11-09 |website=CNN}}</ref> 

===Cash App===
{{Main|Cash App}}

Launched in October 2013, [[Cash App]] (formerly Square Cash) is a digital wallet which allows sending and receiving money, investing in stocks or bitcoin, and filing taxes.<ref name=":24" /><ref name=":8">{{Cite web |last=Hamburger |first=Ellis |date=October 15, 2013 |title=Square Cash lets anyone with a debit card send money instantly over email |url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/10/15/4842518/square-cash-send-money-over-email-iphone-android |access-date=December 20, 2020 |website=The Verge |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":9">{{Cite web |last=Freitas |first=Taylor |date=April 29, 2022 |title=What is Cash App and how does it work? |url=https://www.zdnet.com/finance/what-is-cash-app-and-how-does-it-work-a-comprehensive-guide/ |access-date=October 30, 2023 |website=ZDNET |language=en}}</ref> In March 2015, the firm introduced Square Cash for businesses, which includes the ability for individuals, organizations, and business owners to use a unique username, known as a $cashtag, to send and receive money.<ref>{{Cite web |date=March 23, 2015 |title=Square Introduces Square Cash for Businesses, With a Low 1.5 Percent Processing Fee |url=http://recode.net/2015/03/23/square-introduces-square-cash-for-businesses-with-a-low-1-5-percent-processing-fee/ |work=Re/code}}</ref> As of 2023, Cash App also offers a savings account and a debit card, and services such as direct deposit and investing in stocks and Bitcoin.<ref name=":10">{{Cite web |last=Staples |first=Ana |date=August 22, 2023 |title=What is Cash App and how does it work? |url=https://www.cnbc.com/select/what-is-cash-app/ |access-date=October 30, 2023 |website=CNBC |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":11">{{Cite web |last=Papandrea |first=Dawn |date=August 28, 2023 |title=How to Use Cash App |url=https://www.usnews.com/banking/articles/how-to-use-cash-app |website=[[U.S. News & World Report]]}}</ref> In March 2023,'' [[USA Today]]'' reported that Cash App offered a free tax-filing service while cautioning that it didn't accommodate "every tax situation" and didn't offer "live tax support".<ref name=":12">{{Cite web |last=Jones |first=Jenn |date=September 11, 2023 |title=Best tax software of November 2023 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/money/blueprint/taxes/best-tax-software/ |access-date=November 9, 2023 |website=USA TODAY Blueprint |language=en-US}}</ref> In October 2023, it was reported that Cash App also allowed users to borrow up to $200 from the app, and that "not everyone is an eligible user for this feature".<ref name=":13">{{Cite web |last=Moorhead |first=Caitlyn |date=October 16, 2023 |title=Cash App Borrow: How To Borrow Money on Cash App |url=https://www.gobankingrates.com/banking/technology/cash-app-borrow/ |access-date=October 30, 2023 |website=GOBankingRates |language=en}}</ref>

In February 2024, Block reported 56 million "monthly active users" for Cash App.<ref name=":1" />

===Afterpay===
{{Main|Afterpay}}
Afterpay is an Australian digital payment platform in which a bought product can be paid off in four installments. This idea made in 2008 by a then eighteen-year-old Nick Molnar was geared towards millennials and inspired by the aftermath of the 2008 Global Financial Crisis. Molnar and Partner/ Co-founder Anthony Eisen launched their platform in 2014 and in four years their product reached a market capitalization of around $3.3 billion. In February 2020, Afterpay was reported to have 3.6 million active customers in the US, 3.1 million in Australia and New Zealand, and 600,000 in the UK. According to [[ABC News (Australia)]] in August 2021, Afterpay had operations in the U.S., Canada and New Zealand, as well as in the U.K., France, Italy and Spain as Clearpay.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Whitson |first1=Rhiana |last2=Chalmers |first2=Stephanie |date=2021-08-01 |title=Afterpay shares surge after US giant Square launches biggest buyout in Australian corporate history |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2021-08-02/square-to-buy-afterpay-in-39-billion-deal-buy-now-pay-later/100341852 |access-date=2024-11-09 |work=[[ABC News (Australia)]] |language=en-AU}}</ref> In the same month, Afterpay and Block announced that Afterpay would be acquired by Block.<ref>{{Cite web |date=August 1, 2021 |title=Afterpay to be acquired by Square in $39 billion deal |url=https://www.smartcompany.com.au/startupsmart/news/afterpay-acquired-square-39-billion/ |access-date=April 25, 2022 |website=SmartCompany |language=en-US}}</ref> Block paid US$29 billion in stock for the acquisition and the process was finalized in January 2022. Molnar and Eisen continued to lead Afterpay's merchant and consumer businesses following the acquisition.<ref name="completed acquistion">{{cite press release|title=Block, Inc. Completes Acquisition of Afterpay|url=https://investors.block.xyz/news/news-details/2022/Block-Inc.-Completes-Acquisition-of-Afterpay/default.aspx|publisher=Block, Inc.|date=January 31, 2022}}</ref><ref name=":14">{{Cite web |last=Gariffo |first=Michael |date=February 1, 2022 |title=Block completes acquisition of "buy now, pay later" specialist Afterpay |url=https://www.zdnet.com/finance/block-completes-acquisition-of-buy-now-pay-later-specialist-afterpay/ |access-date=October 30, 2023 |website=ZDNET |language=en}}</ref>

As of 2023, Afterpay serves 24&nbsp;million users and 348,000 merchants,<ref name=":110">{{Cite web |last=Edmunds |first=Susan |date=2024-07-25 |title=Here's why it could get harder to extend your Afterpay |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/business/523065/here-s-why-it-could-get-harder-to-extend-your-afterpay |access-date=2024-11-26 |website=[[Radio New Zealand]] |language=en-nz}}</ref><ref name=":310">{{Cite web |last=Mucklejohn |first=Lars |date=2024-11-14 |title=UK set for buy-now pay-later revolution, says Clearpay’s Nick Molnar |url=https://www.cityam.com/uk-set-for-buy-now-pay-later-revolution-says-clearpays-nick-molnar/ |access-date=2024-11-27 |website=[[City A.M.]]}}</ref> processing US$27.3 billion in payments annually.<ref name=":42">{{Cite web |last=Shen |first=Lucinda |date=2024-02-23 |title=Afterpay, Block's BNPL platform, begins growing again |url=https://www.axios.com/pro/fintech-deals/2024/02/23/afterpay-blocks-bnpl-platform-begins-growing-again |access-date=2024-11-27 |website=[[Axios (website)|Axios]]}}</ref> It also ranks among the three most-used BNPL services globally.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Mullen |first=Caitlin |date=2023-11-09 |title=Breaking down buy now, pay later |url=https://www.retaildive.com/news/buy-now-pay-later-installment-payments-affirm-afterpay-klarna-paypal-regulation/699042/ |access-date=2024-12-12 |website=[[Industry Dive|Retail Dive]] |language=en-US}}</ref>

=== Bitkey ===
{{Main|Bitkey}}

In December 2023, Block launched Bitkey, a self-custody [[Bitcoin]] hardware wallet, in 95 countries including the U.S., the U.K., Canada, Nigeria, Argentina, Mexico, and India. The wallet allows investors to own, manage and store their Bitcoin without relying on third-party exchanges or custodians. Bitkey includes a mobile app, hardware device, and a set of recovery tools in case the customer loses the phone, their hardware or both. The wallet cannot access or move a customer's Bitcoin without them.<ref name=":18" /><ref name=":19" /><ref>{{Cite web |last=Ghosh |first=Debangana |date=2024-03-13 |title=India has a good mix of Bitcoin use cases; is way more tech savvy: Block Inc's Max Guise |url=https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/technology/india-has-a-good-mix-of-bitcoin-use-cases-is-way-more-tech-savvy-block-incs-max-guise-12452801.html |access-date=2024-11-22 |website=[[Network18_Group#Digital_and_publishing_divisions|moneycontrol.com]]}}</ref> In October 2024, TIME named Bitkey as one of the "best inventions of 2024".<ref name=":39" /><ref name=":40" />

=== Bitcoin mining system ===
In April 2024, Block announced it had finished developing its own standalone three-nanometer bitcoin mining chip and was working through the design with a semiconductor foundry. The company reportedly aimed at building a "full bitcoin mining system", stating that its goal was to decentralize both the supply of bitcoin mining hardware and the distribution of hashrate.<ref name=":30" /> In July 2024, Block signed an agreement to supply its chips to bitcoin miner "Core Scientific".<ref name=":29" /><ref name=":31" />

=== Tidal ===
{{Main|Tidal (service)}}

Tidal is a high-definition [[music streaming service]] with a catalog of over 100 million songs across various genres. It offers both a subscription plan and an ad-supported free plan.<ref name=":15">{{Cite magazine |last=Gibson |first=Megan |date=2015-01-30 |title=Jay Z To Buy Streaming Music Service Aspiro for $56 Million |url=https://time.com/3689197/jay-z-aspiro-streaming-service/ |access-date=2024-11-09 |magazine=TIME |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":34">{{Cite magazine |last=Jancer |first=Matt |date=2023-05-15 |title=The Best Music Streaming Apps to Get Your Groove On |url=https://www.wired.com/gallery/best-music-streaming-apps/ |access-date=2024-11-13 |magazine=WIRED |language=en-US}}</ref> Originally launched in 2014 by [[Aspiro]], a Norwegian company, Tidal was purchased in 2015 by American rapper [[Jay-Z]] for $56 million, reportedly to "give artists more control over the distribution of their music".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Sisario |first=Ben |date=March 13, 2015 |title=Jay Z Buys the Music Streaming Firm, Aspiro |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/14/business/media/jay-z-buys-the-music-streaming-firm-aspiro.html |access-date=April 25, 2022 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=":35">{{Cite web |last=Jarvey |first=Natalie |date=2021-03-04 |title=Square Acquires Majority Stake in Jay-Z's Tidal for $297 Million |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/business/digital/square-acquires-majority-stake-in-jay-zs-tidal-for-297-million-4143203/ |access-date=2024-11-13 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |language=en-US}}</ref> At that time, Tidal was available in the U.S., Canada, the U.K., Republic of Ireland, Finland, the Netherlands, Belgium and Luxembourg.<ref name=":15" /> In 2021, Block took majority ownership of Tidal for $297 million,<ref name=":17" /> stating it aimed to find "new ways for artists to support their work" and to create "tools that can help support musicians' businesses".<ref name=":36">{{Cite news |last=Sweney |first=Mark |date=2021-03-04 |title=Jay-Z sells majority stake in Tidal music streaming service to Jack Dorsey's Square |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2021/mar/04/jay-z-sells-majority-stake-in-tidal-music-streaming-service-to-jack-dorseys-square |access-date=2024-11-13 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref name=":35" /> Tidal was then operating in a streaming market dominated by [[Spotify]] and others, and was paying "better royalty rates" to artists than its rivals including Spotify.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Hussain |first1=Noor Zainab |last2=Culliford |first2=Elizabeth |author-link2= |last3=Dave |first3=Paresh |date=2021-03-05 |title=Square's $297 million deal for Jay Z's music service Tidal may bring blockchain to masses |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/technology/squares-297-million-deal-for-jay-zs-music-service-tidal-may-bring-blockchain-idUSKBN2AW1N8/ |access-date=2024-11-09 |website=Reuters}}</ref><ref name=":36" /> In May 2023, [[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] reported that Tidal's “Direct Artist Payouts” scheme, in which up to 10 percent of a user's subscription fee was delivered to the artists they listened to most, had been discontinued in 2022. According to Wired, the scheme was "thoughtful" and supportive of bands and artists, and its closure reduced some of Tidal's market differentiation.<ref name=":34" /> In November 2024, Block announced it was "scaling back" investments in Tidal after reports emerged that the company was laying off Tidal employees.<ref name=":32" /><ref name=":33" /><ref name=":37" /><ref name=":38">{{Cite web |last=Fielding |first=Sarah |date=2024-10-31 |title=Tidal, which is in dire need of some good marketing, lays off its entire product marketing team |url=https://www.engadget.com/entertainment/music/tidal-which-is-in-dire-need-of-some-good-marketing-lays-off-its-entire-product-marketing-team-143045120.html |access-date=2024-11-14 |website=Engadget |language=en-US}}</ref> Block added that it was eliminating Tidal's product management and product marketing functions entirely and that Tidal would become a smaller entity, focusing on fewer areas with a more sustained approach to product development.<ref name=":38" />

==Financials==
Square received [[Angel investor|angel investments]] from [[Marissa Mayer]], [[Kevin Rose]], [[Biz Stone]], [[Dennis Crowley]], [[Shawn Fanning]], [[MC Hammer]], and [[Esther Dyson]].{{citation needed|date=November 2019}} Since then, it has raised several additional rounds of funding:
* Series A funding from [[Khosla Ventures]]<ref name=rounds />
* Series B funding from [[Sequoia Capital]]<ref name=rounds />
* Series C funding from [[Kleiner Perkins]]<ref name=rounds>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2015/11/09/square-ipo-will-net-big-win-for-one-firm.html |title=On paper, Khosla's firm could net a massive return on Square IPO |date=November 9, 2015 |work=[[CNBC]] |last=Taylor |first=Harriet}}</ref>
* Series D funding from [[Citigroup|Citi Ventures]], Rizvi Traverse Management, and Starbucks<ref name="seriesD">{{Cite web |last=Square Inc. |date=December 18, 2014 |title=Square A milestone: We're now 1,000 employees strong. |url=https://www.linkedin.com/company/square |access-date=December 18, 2014 |publisher=Linkedin.com}}</ref>
* Series E funding from [[Goldman Sachs]], Rizvi Traverse Management, and [[GIC Private Limited]]<ref>{{Cite news |last=Isaac |first=Mike |date=October 5, 2014 |title=Square Raises $150 Million at a $6 Billion Valuation |work=The New York Times |url=http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/10/05/square-raises-150-million-at-a-6-billion-valuation/?_r=0}}</ref>

The company's valuation in October 2014 was $6 billion.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Rao |first=Leena |date=October 5, 2014 |title=Square Closes $150 Million Round At $6 Billion Valuation |work=Fortune |url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/10/05/square-closes-150-round-at-6-billion-valuation/}}</ref> On November 19, 2015, Square had its IPO on the New York Stock Exchange with an initial valuation of $2.9 billion, down by more than half from its last valuation in October 2014 at $6 billion. The series E funding shares had different rights than the common shares sold at the IPO, therefore the $6 billion 'valuation' from October 2014 is wrong. Although the firm was yet to make a profit as of 2015 and had lost $420 million since 2012, it had decreased its losses from 44% of revenues to 16% in the six months leading up to its IPO.<ref name="economist_ipo">{{Cite news |date=November 21, 2015 |title=Square's IPO: Swiped |publisher=The Economist |url=https://www.economist.com/news/finance-and-economics/21678809-profitless-payment-firm-goes-public-swiped |access-date=November 20, 2015}}</ref> For the fiscal year 2018, Square reported losses of US$38 million, with an annual revenue of US$3.299 billion, an increase of 49.0% over the previous fiscal cycle.

